This was just a simplification of my solution for the preceding problem, [N-Queens](https://leetcode.com/problems/n-queens/discuss/1555836/Python-recursive-solution-28-32ms-(less~99)), so I found it interesting that the problems are presented in this order.

It led me to realize, however, that I don't need to track the locations of queens (2D array) to generate the solutions for N-Queens (though it's faster). The location of the queens can be inferred from the state of the three arrays (e.g. are the current square's column and two diagonals all non-vacant?).

```
class Solution(object):
  def recurse(self, n, row, cols, diagsA, diagsB):
    if row == n:
      return 1
    r = 0
    for col in range(0, n):
      if cols[col] or diagsA[col + row] or diagsB[col - row]:
        continue
      cols[col] = diagsA[col + row] = diagsB[col - row] = True
      r += self.recurse(n, row + 1, cols, diagsA, diagsB)
      cols[col] = diagsA[col + row] = diagsB[col - row] = False
    return r


  def totalNQueens(self, n):
    cols = [0] * n
    diagsA = [0] * (n * 2 - 1)
    diagsB = [0] * (n * 2 - 1)
    return self.recurse(n, 0, cols, diagsA, diagsB)
```

